  <text>
    <front>
      <div type="editorial_desc">
        <p>In this cartoon commentary on the presidential election of 1864, Union general and
          Democratic presidential candidate George McClellan is shown holding the lapels of the
          coats of President Abraham Lincoln, who was then running for re-election on the Republican
          ticket, and Confederate president Jefferson Davis, apparently in an effort to stop them
          from fighting. Lincoln, who insists on abolition, and Davis, who insists on separation of
          the Confederate states from the Union, are each pulling on opposite sides of a map of the
          United States, tearing it down the middle. This is one of the few cartoons published in
          the run-up to the 1864 election that is sympathetic to McClellan. In this cartoon,
          McClellan is depicted as a mature leader who puts the preservation of the United States
          above all other priorities. In contrast, Lincoln is shown pursuing abolition at the
          expense of establishing peace, and tearing the country apart in the process.</p>
      </div>
    </front>
    <body>
      <div type="image_transcription" n="1" facs="#title">
        <head>
          <supplied resp="editorial">Title</supplied>
